		<marginalia book_id="FolgersHa2" hand="Italian" id="Ha2.178v_0001" marginalia_continues_from="Ha2.179r_0001" marginalia_from_transcription="Ha2.179r.xml">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						<!-- Continued from facing page, left margin, Ha2.179r --> [p. 181: Vnus liber, pragmaticè prudens, et efficax, plus valet, quàm Centum
						vulgariter docti: nec tantùm possunt mille scholastica opera quantu[m]]
						Vnum solidè pragmaticum. In paucis libris, plurimu[m] scientia[e]: in multis,
						minimum. Quod petis, intus habes: exceptis Necessarijs;
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="270" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						paucissimis Singularibus.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>[p. 181: One book that is pragmatically prudent and efficient, is worth more than a hundred commonly taught: nor can thousand scholastic works be so great as] one complete pragmatic book. In a few books, there are many things of science: in many books, there is a minimum of it.
			What you strive for, you have within: with the necessary things taken out; with the fewest singular things.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
